{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"22cd70d8-b407-4b3f-8d74-fce256efa1ab","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<machine>.ips`. Recent crashes appear here within seconds.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   # Check/enable core dumps\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   # Cores go to /cores/core.<pid>\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n   Core dumps are disabled by default on macOS and require SIP adjustments on newer versions.\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` crash report includes the stack trace, exception type, and faulting address — often enough to diagnose NativeAOT crashes without a full core dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e7962f4c-a1d1-4308-8e8c-5137de6cb324","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":284,"requestId":"C3C9:86E8:1CE720F:207E2C0:6A07C249"},"id":"1d622c41-0cdf-42bc-9d55-877ede5d7352","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:03:13.542Z","parentId":"f668d32e-066c-4de9-85bb-3c8c220dd27f"}
